"Rasch P.J., Latham J., Chen C.-C.","Geoengineering by cloud seeding: Influence on sea ice and climate system",2009,"Environmental Research Letters","4","4", 045112,"","",,,10.1088/1748-9326/4/4/045112,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-76149088442&partnerID=40&md5=664289789a70cd99219bf5b2296eb038","Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, MSIN K9-34, 902 Battelle Boulevard, Richland, WA 99352, United States; National Center for Atmospheric Research, PO Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80303, United States; SEAES, University of Manchester, PO Box 88, Manchester M60 1QD, United Kingdom","Rasch, P.J., Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, MSIN K9-34, 902 Battelle Boulevard, Richland, WA 99352, United States; Latham, J., National Center for Atmospheric Research, PO Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80303, United States, SEAES, University of Manchester, PO Box 88, Manchester M60 1QD, United Kingdom; Chen, C.-C., National Center for Atmospheric Research, PO Box 3000, Boulder, CO 80303, United States","General circulation model computations using a fully coupled ocean-atmosphere model indicate that increasing cloud reflectivity by seeding maritime boundary layer clouds with particles made from seawater may compensate for some of the effects on climate of increasing greenhouse gas concentrations. The chosen seeding strategy (one of many possible scenarios) can restore global averages of temperature, precipitation and sea ice to present day values, but not simultaneously. The response varies nonlinearly with the extent of seeding, and geoengineering generates local changes to important climatic features. The global tradeoffs of restoring ice cover, and cooling the planet, must be assessed alongside the local changes to climate features. © 2009 IOP Publishing Ltd.","Aerosol indirect effect; Climate change; Cloud seeding; Geo-engineering; Global warming","Climate change; Climate models; Global warming; Sea ice; Seawater effects; Aerosol indirect effect; Boundary layer clouds; Climatic features; Gas concentration; General circulation model; Geo-engineering; Ocean-atmosphere models; Seeding strategies; Cloud seeding",,,,,,"Summary for policymakers (2007) Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group i to the 4th Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 1-18. , Solomon S, Qin D, Manning M, Chen Z, Marquis M, Avery K, Tignor M and Miller H (ed) Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Wigley, T.M.L., A combined mitigation/geoengineering approach to climate stabilization (2006) Science, 314, pp. 452-454; Latham, J., Control of global warming? (1990) Nature, 347, pp. 339-340; Latham, J., Rasch, P.J., Chen, C.-C., Kettles, L., Gadian, A., Gettelman, A., Morrison, H., Choularton, T.W., Global temperature stabilization via controlled albedo enhancement of low-level maritime clouds (2008) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A, 366, pp. 3969-3987; Salter, S., Sortino, G., Latham, J., Sea-going hardware for the cloud albedo method of reversing global warming (2008) Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A, 366, pp. 2989-4006; Twomey, S., Influence of pollution on the short-wave albedo of clouds (1977) J. Atmos. Sci., 34, pp. 1149-1152; Albrecht, B.A., Aerosols, cloud microphysics and fractional cloudiness (1989) Science, 245, pp. 1227-1230; Platnick, S., Oreopoulos, L., Radiative susceptibility of cloudy atmospheres to droplet number perturbations: 1. Theoretical analysis and examples from MODIS (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D14S20; Oreopoulos, L., Platnick, S., Radiative susceptibility of cloudy atmospheres to droplet number perturbations: 2. Global analysis from MODIS (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D14S21; Quaas, J., Feichter, J., Climate change mitigation by seeding marine boundary layer clouds (2008) Consequences of Geo-Engineering and Mitigation As Strategies for Responding to Anthropogenic Greenhouse Gas Emissions at the EGU General Assembly, , Vienna, April 2008) Poster paper; Ramanathan, V., Cloud-radiative forc